<br>
This is an attempt to make a more accurate model of casting efficiency.<br>
<br>
The &quot;model&quot; casters are going to choose the most efficient damage-per-mana spell, and chain cast spells until they cycle.  An efficiency greedy chain cast, in other words.<br>
<br>
Mana preservation items are going to be modeled as a random amount saved.  This matches some in game tests I did -- I'm convinced at least.<br>
<br>
SCM 3 and Spec will reduce mana costs by 25%.<br>
<br>
The best gear that has dropped in game will be assumed.  It is easier to compare classes at the top of the game than at some arguable intermediate point.<br>
<br>
Full SCF and FOM give a 14% crit rate.<br>
Full SCF, SCFM and FOMM give a 20% crit rate<br>
<br>
I've got a program set up to use the above heuristics to find the optimal nuke order, and effective ratio of each class's chain nuke options.  Anything wrong from the above?<br>
<br>
/em runs off to enter spell specs into the proggy.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=aauminki>Aauminki</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 97<br> <font color=#ffffff>(3/11/03 6:30 pm)</font><br>     <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Efficient Chain Nuking</span><hr size=1> I thought SCM3 was 11% flat saved and Spec:200 was 12% making it 23% total? Guess it doesnt matter at all since it's applied to all classes.<br>
<br>
I'm not sure what you are trying to accomplish by making this comparison though. It would make more sense to simulate different kinds of fights with a set time-limit and try to hit zero mana at the end of that time frame. <p><big><center><b><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=370955 target=blank>Master Aauminki Iceblade</a><br><a href=http://www.vazaelle.dk target=blank>Caer Cadarn</a></big><br>Vazaelle Server</center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=laeyakk>Laeyakk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 55<br> <font color=#ffffff>(3/12/03 12:02 am)</font><br>     <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Efficient Chain Nuking</span><hr size=1> Because it generates very nice nuke sequences.<br>
<br>
For example, for wizards, it does:<br>
Ancient: Destruction of Ice<br>
Ice spear of Solist<br>
Strike of Solusk<br>
<br>
and repeat.  On a mob with low resists, that's a damn optimal way to dump your mana.<br>
<br>
My attempt at using mages was equally reasonable.<br>
Maelstrom of Thunder<br>
Sun Vortex<br>
Sun Vortex<br>
<br>
The sort of nuke patterns you'd use in both a raid or an xp group.<br>
<br>
In theory, I could generate 50 times as much data, but I think this will be good enough.<br>
